### Monodromy matrices for difference Schrödinger equations

Let $h>0$ and $v:{\mathbb R}\to {\mathbb C}$. The difference Schrödinger equation $$\label{diff-Sch}
   \psi(x+h)+\psi(x-h)+v(x)\psi(x)=E\psi(x),\quad x\in {\mathbb R},$$ is equivalent to <a href="#eq:matrix" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:matrix">[eq:matrix]</a> with $$\label{eq:M:Shcr}
 M(z)=\begin{pmatrix} E-v(x) & -1 \\ 1 & 0\end{pmatrix}.$$ More precisely, a function $\Psi:{\mathbb R}\mapsto C^2$ satisfies <a href="#eq:matrix" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:matrix">[eq:matrix]</a> with this matrix if and only if $\Psi(x)=\begin{pmatrix}\psi(x) \\ \psi(x-h)\end{pmatrix}$, and $\psi$ is a solution to <a href="#diff-Sch" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="diff-Sch">[diff-Sch]</a>. This allows to turn the observations made for <a href="#eq:matrix" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:matrix">[eq:matrix]</a> into observations for <a href="#diff-Sch" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="diff-Sch">[diff-Sch]</a> .  
Let $\psi_1$ and $\psi_2$ be two solutions to <a href="#eq:matrix" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:matrix">[eq:matrix]</a>. The expression $$%
  \{\psi_1(x),\psi_2(x)\}=\psi_1(x+h)\psi_2(x)-\psi_1(x)\psi_2(x+h),$$ their Wronskian, is $h$-periodic in $x$.  
Assume that the Wronskian is constant and nonzero. Then $\psi_{1,2}$ form a basis in the space of solutions, and a function $\psi$ satisfies <a href="#diff-Sch" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="diff-Sch">[diff-Sch]</a> if and only if $$\label{eq:three-solutions}
  \psi(x)=a(x)\psi_1(x)+b(x)\psi_2(x),$$ where $a$ and $b$ are $h$-periodic coefficients. One easily proves that $$\label{eq:periodic-coef}
  a(x)=\frac{\{\psi(x),\,\psi_2(x)\}}{\{\psi_1(x),\,\psi_2(x)\}},\quad 
  b(x)=\frac{\{\psi_1(x),\,\psi\,(x)\}}{\{\psi_1(x),\,\psi_2(x)\}}.$$ If $v$ is $1$-periodic, the functions $x\to \psi_1(x+1)$ and $x\to 
\psi_2(x+1)$ are also solutions to <a href="#diff-Sch" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="diff-Sch">[diff-Sch]</a>, and one can write $$\label{eq:MM-def} \Psi (x + 1) = M_1 (x / h) \Psi (x), \quad \Psi (x) =
  \begin {pmatrix} \psi_1 (x) \\ \psi_2 (x) \end {pmatrix}, \quad x \in {\mathbb R},$$ where $M_1$ is a $1$-periodic $2\times2$ matrix. It is the matrix monodromy corresponding to $\psi_1$ and $\psi_2$. It coincides with a monodromy matrix for <a href="#eq:matrix" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:matrix">[eq:matrix]</a> with the matrix <a href="#eq:M:Shcr" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:M:Shcr">[eq:M:Shcr]</a>.

\end{gathered}$$ Let $V=(v_+\;v_-)$. We represent a vector-valued solution to <a href="#eq:M1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:M1">[eq:M1]</a> in the form $$\label{eq:psi-phi}
    \psi(x)= V\phi(x).$$ Then $\phi$ satisfies equation <a href="#eq:phi" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:phi">[eq:phi]</a> with $$\label{eq:theta-Delta}
    U=q\cos\alpha +Q \quad \text{and}
    \quad \Delta(x)=\frac1p\,V^{-1} \tilde M(x)V.$$ Let us determine the conditions under which $U$ and $\Delta$ from <a href="#eq:theta-Delta" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:theta-Delta">[eq:theta-Delta]</a> satisfy the assumptions of Proposition <a href="#le:resolvent-set:1" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="le:resolvent-set:1">2</a>. Let $$\label{eq:cond1}
    q^2\cos^2\alpha>1.$$ We can and do assume that $Q>0$ and consider the case where $q\cos\alpha>1$. The complementary case is analyzed similarly.  
We have $U>1$, and the first condition in <a href="#f-d-e-on-R1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="f-d-e-on-R1">[f-d-e-on-R1]</a> is satisfied.  
Now, let us estimate the entries of $\Delta$. One has $$|\sin\alpha|=\sqrt{1-\cos^2\alpha}\le \sqrt{1-\frac1{q^2}}\le
  \left|\frac{\lambda_1}\tau\right|,\quad
    Q=\sqrt{\left(1+\frac{\lambda_1^2}{\tau^2}\right)\cos^2\alpha-1}
    \le\left|\frac{\lambda_1}\tau\right|.$$ Therefore and as $\lambda_1\le |\tau|$, the second entries of $v_\pm$ are uniformly bounded : $$\left|\frac{p}s \left( q\cos\alpha-\frac1qe^{i\alpha}\mp Q\right)\right|
 =\left|\frac{p}{qs}\right|\left|\frac{\lambda_1^2}{\tau^2}\cos\alpha-
   i\sin\alpha\mp qQ\right|\le C\left|\frac{p\lambda_1}{qs\tau}\right|=C.$$ As $\det V=-2pQ/s$, this estimate implies that, for all $i,j\in\{1,2\}$, $$%
  \max_{x\in{\mathbb R}} |\Delta_{ij}(x)|\le C\left|\frac{s\tau}{p^2Q}\right|=
  C\left|\frac{\lambda_1}{pqQ}\right|< C\frac{\lambda_1}{Q}.$$ Therefore, the second condition from <a href="#f-d-e-on-R1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="f-d-e-on-R1">[f-d-e-on-R1]</a> is satisfied if $$\label{eq:phi:1}
  \frac{U-U^{-1}}2=Q\ge C\frac{\lambda_1}{Q}
  \quad \Longleftrightarrow\quad
  q^2\cos^2\alpha\ge 1+C\lambda_1.$$ Clearly, this condition implies <a href="#eq:cond1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:cond1">[eq:cond1]</a> and, as $L=2pq\cos\alpha$, it is equivalent to <a href="#cond:gap" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="cond:gap">[cond:gap]</a>.  
Let assume that <a href="#eq:phi:1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:phi:1">[eq:phi:1]</a> is satisfied. Then, using Proposition <a href="#le:resolvent-set:1" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="le:resolvent-set:1">2</a> and formula <a href="#eq:psi-phi" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:psi-phi">[eq:psi-phi]</a>, we construct two vector-valued solutions $\psi_\pm=V\phi_\pm$ to the monodromy equation. As $p(U^{-1}+U)/2=pq\cos\alpha=L/2$, estimates <a href="#est:phi" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="est:phi">[est:phi]</a> imply the estimates for $\psi_\pm$ from Proposition <a href="#pro:M1:gaps" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="pro:M1:gaps">1</a>. Furthermore, one has $$\det(\psi_+(x),\psi_-(x))=
\det V\,\det(\phi_+(x),\phi_-(x))=\det V\ne 0.$$ The proof is complete. ◻

</div>

### Locations of gaps

Inequality <a href="#cond:gap:1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="cond:gap:1">[cond:gap:1]</a> can be rewritten as $\frac{X^2-C\lambda_1}{1+X^2}\ge \sin^2\alpha$, and assuming that $\lambda_1/X^2$ and $X^2$ are sufficiently small, we transform it to the form $$\label{cond:gap:2}
 |X|\,(1+O(\lambda_1/X^2)+O(X^2))\ge |\sin \alpha|,$$ and see that there are gaps containing the points $E_k$ defined by the relations $$\label{def:Ek} 
 E_k=2\cos(2\pi p_k),\quad \alpha(p_k)= \pi k,\quad k\in\mathbb Z$$ To continue, we need the following two lemmas:

<div id="le:as:alpha" class="lemma">

