### Integral representation

We construct solutions in the form: $$\label{mu:form}
\mu\,(z)=\frac1{\sqrt{h}}\int_{\gamma}e^{\frac{2\pi izk}h}\, v\,(k)\,dk,$$ where $\gamma$ is a curve in the complex plane that we describe later, and $v$ is a function analytic in a sufficiently large neighborhood of $\gamma$. The function $\mu$ satisfies <a href="#mu:eq" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="mu:eq">[mu:eq]</a> if $$\begin{aligned}
%
v(k+h)=2(\cos (2\pi p)-\cos (2\pi k))\,v(k).
\end{aligned}$$ We note that $$2(\cos(2\pi p)-\cos (2\pi k))=-e^{2\pi ik}\,(1-e^{-2\pi 
i(k-p)})\,(1-e^{-2\pi i(k+p)}).$$ Therefore, one can choose $$\label{v:form}
v(k)=e^{\frac{i\pi k^2}{h}-\frac{\pi i k}{h}-\pi ik}\, 
\sigma_{\pi h}(2\pi(k-p-{\textstyle \frac h2-\frac12}))\,
\sigma_{\pi h}(2\pi(k+p-{\textstyle \frac h2 -\frac12})),$$ where $\sigma_a$ is a solution to <a href="#eq:sigma" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:sigma">[eq:sigma]</a>. In this paper, we use the meromorphic solution described in Section <a href="#sec:sigma" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="sec:sigma">8</a>.

### Properties of the function $v$

