k=\pm p-lh-m,\quad l,m=0,1,2,3\dots.$$ Let $l_\pm=\pm p-(-\infty,0]$. The rays $l_\pm$ contain all the poles of $v$.  
Below, for $k\in{\mathbb C}$, we write $r={\rm Re}\,k$ and $q={\rm Im}\,k$.  
Let $|q|> C\,|r|$. Corollary <a href="#cor:sigma:2" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="cor:sigma:2">9</a> implies the uniform asymptotic representations $$\begin{gathered}
\label{v:down}
v(k)= v_-\,e^{\frac{i\pi\left(k-{\textstyle \frac12-\frac h2} 
\right)^2}{h}+o(1)},\quad
v_-=-ie^{-\frac{i\pi}{4 h}-\frac{\pi ih}4},\qquad q\to-\infty,
