*Proof.* Let $p\in P$. Pick $Y$ sufficiently large. For $y\ge - Y$, the estimate for $\mu$ follows directly from Proposition <a href="#pro:mu:up" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="pro:mu:up">4</a>. For $|y|\le Y$, the estimate for $\mu'$ follows from the estimate for $\mu$ and the Cauchy estimates for the derivatives of analytic functions (as $X$ and $Y$ were chosen rather arbitrarily). Let $y\ge Y$ and $|x|\le X$. The first estimate in <a href="#mu-est" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="mu-est">[mu-est]</a> implies that, in the $(h/y)$-neighborhood of $z$, $\mu$ is bounded by $H w(x,y)$ (we again use the fact that $X$ and $Y$ were chosen rather arbitrarily). This and the Cauchy estimates for the derivatives of analytic functions lead then to the estimate $|\mu'(z)|\le yH w(x,y)$. This completes the proof of <a href="#mu-est" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="mu-est">[mu-est]</a> for $y\ge -Y$.

Let us prove <a href="#mu-est" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="mu-est">[mu-est]</a> for $y\le -Y$. Pick $0<\alpha<1$. Let $|x|\le X$,  $y\le -Y$ and ${\rm Re}\,p\ge \alpha h/2$. Estimate <a href="#est:a0" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="est:a0">[est:a0]</a> and Proposition <a href="#pro:mu:down" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="pro:mu:down">5</a> imply that $$\label{est:mu:rough:1}
|\mu(z) e^{-\frac{2\pi ipz}h}|\le H.$$ By means of the Cauchy estimates for the derivatives of analytic functions we get the estimate $$\label{est:mu:rough:2}
