The rest of the section is devoted to the proof of Theorem <a href="#psi0" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="psi0">7</a>.

Let us explain the idea of the proof of Theorem <a href="#psi0" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="psi0">7</a>. Let $\gamma=\{z\in i{\mathbb R}\,:\, y\ge -Y\}$. We study the integral equation $$\label{int-eq}
\psi\,(z)=\mu\,(z+i\xi)-(K\psi)(z),\quad K\psi(z)=\int_{\gamma}
\kappa\,(z,\,z')\psi\,(z')\,dz',\quad z\in \gamma.$$ The kernel $\kappa$ is constructed in terms of $\mu(\cdot+i\xi)$ and $\tilde \mu(\cdot +i\xi)$, two linearly independent solutions to the unperturbed equation <a href="#un-pert-eq" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="un-pert-eq">[un-pert-eq]</a>, $$\begin{gathered}
\kappa\,(z,\,z')= \frac {\lambda}{2ih}\,\Theta\,(z,\,z')\, \frac{
        [\,\mu(z+i\xi)\,\tilde \mu\,(z'+i\xi)-
         \mu\,(z'+i\xi)\,\tilde \mu\,(z+i\xi)\,]}
        {\{\mu,\,\tilde \mu\}}\,e^{2\pi iz'},
        %
\\
\Theta\,(z,\,z')={\mathrm cot}\,\frac{\pi(z'-z)}h\,-i.
%
\end{gathered}$$ Similar integral operators have appeared in . The kernel $\kappa$ can be considered as a difference analog of the resolvent kernel arising in the theory of differential equations. First, we construct a solution to the integral equation <a href="#int-eq" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="int-eq">[int-eq]</a>, and then, we check that it is analytic in $z$ and satisfies the difference equation <a href="#eq:harper" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:harper">[eq:harper]</a>. Finally, we obtain the asymptotics of this solution for $y\to+\infty$ and for $y\sim 0$.

